In this clause two things are to be noticed: first, that the Latin regularly puts an antecedent which is in apposition with something preceding in the relative clause, e.g. “ which kind,” not “a kind which'’; and, second, that a verb which govems the dat. cannot be used in the pass. with a personal subject.
